cs.DS, cs.CG, cs.DM, cs.GT, cs.CC

Reasoning: 
1. cs.DS (Data Structures and Algorithms) - The paper presents a polynomial-time algorithm for solving the minimum multicut problem in planar graphs with fixed k source-sink pairs. This problem is a well-known optimization problem in computer science and falls under the scope of data structures and algorithms.
2. cs.CG (Computational Geometry) - The paper deals with planar graphs and their properties, which is a topic of interest in computational geometry. The algorithm presented in the paper also involves geometric concepts such as planar embeddings and cuts.
3. cs.DM (Discrete Mathematics) - The minimum multicut problem is a combinatorial optimization problem that involves graph theory and discrete mathematics. The paper presents a new result in this area by providing a polynomial-time algorithm for a previously NP-hard problem.
4. cs.GT (Computer Science and Game Theory) - The minimum multicut problem has applications in game theory, particularly in network design and routing games. The paper may be of interest to researchers working in this area.
5. cs.CC (Computational Complexity) - The paper discusses the complexity of the minimum multicut problem and presents a polynomial-time algorithm for a restricted case. This falls under the scope of computational complexity theory, which is concerned with the study of the inherent difficulty of computational problems.
